# reachat CSS Variables and Theming

## CSS Custom Properties

Based on the documentation, reachat uses only **three CSS variables** for theming:

```css
:root {
  --nextra-primary-hue: 212deg;
  --nextra-primary-saturation: 100%;
  --nextra-navbar-height: 4rem;
  --nextra-menu-height: 3.75rem;
  --nextra-banner-height: 2.5rem;
}

.dark {
  --nextra-primary-hue: 204deg;
  --nextra-primary-saturation: 100%;
}
```

The primary difference between light and dark modes is the hue adjustment: **212deg (light) vs 204deg (dark)**.

## Theming Approach

Rather than relying on CSS variables, reachat uses a **JavaScript theme object pattern**. You pass a `ChatTheme` configuration object to the `Chat` component:

```jsx
export default function App() {
  return <Chat theme={theme} ...rest of your props... />;
}
```

The theme uses **Tailwind CSS classes** for styling. Dark mode is applied via the `dark:` prefix convention. For example:

```
'bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-900/60'
'text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-200'
```

## Key Takeaway

reachat doesn't use extensive CSS custom properties. Instead, it leverages **Tailwind utility classes within a TypeScript theme object**, allowing developers to customize every component through className strings rather than CSS variables.
